The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, April 26, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New York, April 25: Tata Consultancy Services (TCS) will open an automotive centre of excellence in Detroit, from where it will provide IT, manufacturing, engineering consulting and services to its North American automotive customers. The centre will be fully functional within the next two months and TCS is planning to hire 50 local automotive professionals in the next 12 to 18 months, the company said.																								 New Delhi, April 25: Reliance Energy has approached banks and financial institutions (FIs) for a Rs 9,000 crore loan for its proposed power plant at Dadri in Uttar Pradesh. Reliance had made a presentation before a consortium of FIs in Mumbai for financing the project with a 90 per cent debt component and 10 per cent equity against the industry norm of 70:30 debt-equity ratio.																								 Mumbai, April 25: Tata Power Company has said the Dabhol project was viable at a tariff of Rs 2.5 per unit. It also described the taking over of the Enron equity in Dabhol Power Company by GE and Bechtel as positive.																								 New Delhi, April 25: Twelve topline merchant bankers, including DSP Merill Lynch, J M Morgan Stanley and HSBC Securities, have expressed interest in acting as lead managers for 5 per cent public offer of shares in NTPC, expected to hit the market later this year.
